class='post-entry post-entry-type-standard post-entry-2722 with_slideshow big-slideshow-post'> <span
class='entry-border-overflow extralight-border'></span><div
class='slideshow_container  big-slideshow'><ul
class='preloading slideshow fade_slider' data-autorotation='false' data-autorotation-timer='5' ><li
data-animation='random'  class='featured featured_container1 caption_left caption_left_framed caption_framed' ><a
href='http://cdn.rottmann.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bac-wordpress-security-chain-lock.jpg?f329b7'><img
src='http://cdn.rottmann.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bac-wordpress-security-chain-lock.jpg?f329b7' title='bac wordpress security chain lock' alt='' data-imgh='415' data-imgw='765' /></a></li></ul></div><h1 class='post-title offset-by-one '> <a
href="http://rottmann.net/2013/01/plugins-i-use-to-secure-my-wordpress-install/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link: Plugins I use to secure my WordPress install">Plugins I use to secure my WordPress install <span
class='post-format-icon minor-meta'></span> </a></h1><div
class="one unit alpha blog-meta"><div
class='side-container side-container-date'><div
class='side-container-inner'> <span
class='date-day'>12</span> <span
class='date-month'>Jan</span></div></div></div><div
class="seven units entry-content"> <span
class='date-container minor-meta meta-color'>12/01/2013</span><p>A couple of my posts have reached thousands of users. Lately, my <a
href="http://www.rottmann.net/2013/01/an-iphone-lovers-confession-i-switched-to-the-nexus-4-completely/">iPhone 5 to Nexus 4 switch</a> got <a
href="http://gizmodo.com/5973073/an-iphone-lovers-confession-i-switched-to-the-nexus-4-completely" target="_blank">republished by GIZMODO</a>, picked up by <a
href="http://readwrite.com/2013/01/04/android-now-outshines-ios-in-almost-every-aspect" target="_blank">ReadWriteWeb</a> and <a
href="http://news.cnet.com/8301-13579_3-57563527-37/android-challenges-the-iphone-in-every-category/" target="_blank">CNET News</a>.</p><p><strong>With increased popularity comes increased risk.</strong></p><p><a
href="http://cdn.rottmann.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Sucuri-SiteCheck-Free-Website-Malware-Scanner.jpg?f329b7"><img
class="alignright  wp-image-2729" alt="Sucuri SiteCheck - Free Website Malware Scanner" src="http://cdn.rottmann.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Sucuri-SiteCheck-Free-Website-Malware-Scanner.jpg?f329b7" width="295" height="358" /></a>rottmann.net, formerly 24100.net, runs on the most current version of WordPress. However, it&#8217;s not a fresh install. Instead, I started the site quite a few years ago, so the current version is one of many updates I&#8217;ve applied over those years.</p><p>Recently, some of my audience <a
href="https://plus.google.com/106658337982640166595/posts" target="_blank">over on Google+</a> pointed out, that their <a
href="http://www.avgthreatlabs.com/" target="_blank">AVG ThreatLab</a> based anti virus tool flagged rottmann.net as potentially infected with a backdoor virus. Interestingly, though <a
href="http://www.google.com/safebrowsing/diagnostic?site=rottmann.net" target="_blank">Google&#8217;s Safe Browsing</a> diagnostic page did not indicate any issues (and still does not), they were right. My in-depth checks with <a
href="http://sitecheck.sucuri.net/results/www.rottmann.net" target="_blank">Sucuri&#8217;s SiteCheck</a> indicated quite a couple of JavaScript and PHP files, that had been altered.</p><p><span
id="more-2722"></span></p><p>It turned out, that over all these years, attackers had used some of the now fixed vulnerabilities in either WordPress&#8217; core or some of the Plugins I&#8217;m using here.</p><p>While none of the stuff that I found could directly harm any of rottmann.net&#8217;s visitors, I started to worry and seriously invested some time to fix all issues.</p><p>AVG ThreatLabs still shows the <strong>cached</strong> results, but rottmann.net has been completely cleaned and all lights are green again.</p><p>In case, you&#8217;ve been running a WordPress install for a while, you might find the following tips valuable:</p><ul><li>By far the most helpful plugin during my quest was <a
href="http://gotmls.net/" target="_blank">GOTMLS.NET</a>&#8216;s <a
href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/gotmls/" target="_blank">Anti-Malware (Get Off Malicious Script)</a>. It allows you to scan your entire WordPress folder structure for altered files and those that look suspicious. It requires you to register with GOTMLS but it&#8217;s well worth the extra steps. Be aware though, in my case the plugin yielded a couple of false positives, primarily because it tends to always flag files, that contain the eval PHP statement.</li><li><a
href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/look-see-security-scanner/" target="_blank">Look-See Security Scanner</a> is a plugin that helps you clean up your WordPress installation and checks whether your current configuration is safe. It does so, by downloading the latest list of standard WordPress files and folders and comparing it with the ones on your web server. In my case, I could get rid of hundreds of orphaned files from previous WordPress installations and identified a couple of PHP scripts, that were modified by attackers.</li><li>The <a
href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/ultimate-security-checker/" target="_blank">Ultimate Security Checker</a> for WordPress provided additional insight, however, it yielded way too many false positives for my taste. A security tool, that makes you wrongly feel insecure in the majority of cases is probably not a good idea. Unfortunately, the File Analysis module did not work at all.</li><li>In case you decide to leverage Sucuri&#8217;s paid services, they&#8217;ve got a WordPress plugin, too. It frequently auto-checks your installation and notifies with email alerts, in case anything needs your attention. I&#8217;ve subscribed to their somewhat pricy services for rottmann.net.</li></ul><p>For quickly checking whether you need to take action, check your site via the following services:</p><ul><li>http://www.avgthreatlabs.com/sitereports/domain/<strong>&lt;your domain here&gt;</strong></li><li>http://sitecheck.sucuri.net/results/<strong>&lt;your domain here&gt;</strong></li><li>http://www.google.com/safebrowsing/diagnostic?site=<strong>&lt;your domain here&gt;</strong></li><li>Reader <a
href="https://plus.google.com/103294523893758106660/posts" target="_blank">Stephan Hochhaus</a> pointed me to the free <a
href="https://detectify.com" target="_blank">Detectify</a>, which allows for scheduled scans.</li></ul><p>Should you run into infected files, there are a couple of alternatives, depending on your skills and how much effort you plan to put into it:</p><ul><li>Sucuri has a paid services. You provide them with temporary FTP or SSH level access and they make sure your install gets completely cleaned within 48 hours.</li><li>I downloaded the latest version of WordPress from wordpress.org and just replaced most of the files on my server with fresh, 100% clean copies. This fixed all of the JavaScript related issues. I did the same with the plugins that were reported to causing problems.</li><li>You might want to start over with a clean WordPress install and use one of the export / import plugins, to move all of your settings and content over.</li></ul><p>Last but not least, <a
href="http://wp.smashingmagazine.com/2012/10/09/four-malware-infections-wordpress/" target="_blank">this October 2012 article in Smashing Magazine</a> provides an in-depth technical overview of WordPress vulnerabilities and measures to protect against them.</p><p>Hope this helps. For questions and comments, <a
href="https://plus.google.com/106658337982640166595/posts" target="_blank">hop over to Google+</a>. Would love to hear from you.<div
